From an opinion piece in the Jerusalem Post, Feb 14, 2023 by Nawaf Obaid and Nimrod Novik: "The Arab Peace Initiative (API) [2002] ... remains the only credible mechanism by which to achieve a permanent and comprehensive peace settlement between Israel and the wider Arab and Muslim worlds. ... Netanyahu’s new policy of prioritizing Israel’s normalization with the kingdom before any tangible progress toward a sustainable peace with the Palestinians ... is simply a non-starter."

The Saudi foreign minister said that normalization of relations will only come after Palestinian statehood which will not come by March 1. Additionally, MBS has laid out a list of conditions that will lead to a breakthrough in relations. These conditions are not as stringent or far off as Palestinian statehood but most do not seem palatable to hardline conservative Israelis and will not be met before March 1

Very unlikely at this point. The Saudi's appear to have ruled out formal recognition without a two-state solution (https://www.timesofisrael.com/saudi-fm-rules-out-normalization-with-israel-without-a-two-state-solution/) and the Netanyahu government has little-to-no interest in such. Saudi Arabia doesn't need to formally recognize Israel to cooperate with them against Iran, which seems to be the main thing that's been driving rapprochement.
It looks like this won't happen without progress on the Palestinian issue, which looks unlikely.

"Normalizing relations" is the word of the day. From the Feb 2 Israeli newspaper Haaretz: "After the UAE, Bahrain and Morocco, Sudan will be the fourth Arab country to join the Abraham Accords and sign a peace agreement with Israel" sometime in 2023.

https://jcpa.org/what-are-the-prospects-for-normalization-between-saudi-arabia-and-israel/ worth reading for all here, an excellent distillation of the situation and views of key actors. Gives me further confidence that on the timeline here, there is really no realistic prospect.

Multiple factors are assessed currently to determine a low probability in this time frame. The Yemeni conflict is showing signs of improvement, meaning it' receiving less Iranian influence. The United States under the Biden administration is showing less preference to Israel as the previous administration. The latest elections in Israel show a right leaning trend. All things considered pressures to normalize relations with Israel in the recent past are not as strong currently.

Saudi Arabia will not normalize ties with Israel in the absence of a two-state solution with the Palestinians, the kingdom’s top diplomat has said, according to a tweet by the foreign ministry on Friday.

Netanyahu is eager to normalize relations, and the Saudis recently have sent signals that they are more concerned about U.S. guarantees than the Palestinian issue. They also let Netanyahu have an interview with Al Arabiya to advocate for normalization.
Passage of time.

Saudi Arabia purportedly wants to normalize relations, but both sides think it's going to take time. The negotiations apparently involve Saudi requesting certain things from the US not relating to Israel, and it's not completely clear to me that the Biden administration would be willing to provide those. So this seems like something that is very likely to happen but could take anywhere from 0.5-2.5 years. I'd give it maybe a 2/3 chance of happening in 2023, but it doesn't seem like negotiations are far enough along for it to happen before March 1, with both sides saying it will take time.https://www.jpost.com/israel-news/article-724199
Reaffirming this forecast based on this NYTimes piece
Saudi Arabia sees the economic advantages of normalizes relations; however, by waiting they know they can extract a few more concessions from the US

Key condition needed for normalisation is the death of King Salman and MbS' accession. On the short timeframe, seems unlikely the accession will happen and enough time will pass for this major step to take place. Moreover, the new Israeli govt will increase anti-Israeli sentiment across the Arab world, including in Saudi. Seems to me that MbS will be better under these circumstances to increase backchannel ties, but a public declaration of normalisation does not seem likely at all.
It's too soon to happen.

Optimism about Saudi normalization with Israel within the next 3 months or so are misplaced. Data on support for the Abraham Accords indicate significant decrease among Arab populations regarding benefits of the accords. While covert discussions around various dynamics between the Israeli’s and Saudi’s have been ongoing for some time, the Saudi perception of what the Accords currently deliver indicate caution rather than haste despite opening its airspace to the Israeli’s. Deep religious divisions involve recognizing the legitimacy of Israel as well as the need of broader Arab regional support for the Accords. While this outcome is likely, the time horizon is further than currently thought possible.

Clear indications now from all sides that this is going ahead. Terms have been set with America (Palestine is off the table) and a subsequent statement from their ambassador seems to indicate that an agreement was made.
Crazier things have happened, but it won't happen on such a timeline
Saudi Arabia wants to normalize ties with Israel - report (Published: DECEMBER 6, 2022)

Relations will continue to improve between the two nations, but I don't think recognition will happen by the question's deadline. I suspect that it'll not happen in 2023 at all, barring a Biden-Harris Administration about-face.

While Saudi Arabia and Israel have been working behind the scenes even since President Trump was President of the United States, the country has said that it will only recognise Israel publicly if there is movement to resolve the Palestinian conflict. This looks unlikely at present.

I wonder whether optimism about some of Saudi Arabia’s recent domestic reforms is creating the perception that it will also change its opinion about this prominent aspect of its foreign policy. But I can’t see why Riyadh would give up some much potential leverage in efforts to create an independent Palestine for… what? I don’t know what is rumored to be on offer for the Saudis to change their position, but it seems highly improbable that they’d abandon their commitment to Palestine on the time frame of this question (and even more improbable that Palestine may be come an independent state before March 1st.)

There are real benefits to Saudi Arabia for normalizing relations with Israel. However, Netanyahu's return to power sadly makes Israel less attractive. My 10% forecast is based on hope as much as it is on rationality.
People on the ground and who seem to be quite well informed and cautious feel like many Arab nations have more to lose than to gain, depending on what the incoming Israeli government does.

This has become far less taboo than historically and common economic interests, position on Iran will allow this to happen, particularly following the precedent of other Arab nations during the Trump presidency. It is still a stretch by March 2023 but could happen later in 2023 or 2024.
There's always a chance.

Saudi Arabia will be busy dealing with its neighbor, Iran, as well as the Qatari World Cup coming up. With Trump likely announcing his candidacy soon, he will want Saudi Arabia to wait until much later than March, 2023 to announce further cooperation with Israel.

After Saudi Arabia expressed its dissatisfaction with US security ties by agreeing with Russia to cut oil production, the US appears likely to punish Saudi Arabia by reducing its security ties (at least symbolically). This will probably further reduce Saudi willingness to please the US by normalizing with Israel.
This will depend on the next president of the US, the next leader of Iran (if there is one), and many other factors. But nothing has changed since the last prediction.

I really doubt anything positive will happen between Saudi Arabia and Israel at this point, because they don't have the incentives to do so. They have both chosen their allies and the other side is not a part of that.

I'm not ruling out that because of the US and Saudi ties going down, that ironically and somehow makes the Saudis and Israelis closer - for whatever reasons. It's possible.

The deteriorating relations between the United States and Saudi Arabia reduces the probability that the U.S. can bring Saudi Arabia and Israel together. Israel is halting efforts to secure arms deals with Saudi for fear of angering the United States. However, in the long run, Saudi Arabia may feel that since it cannot rely on the United States, it will need a stronger relationship with Israel as the most militarily advanced state in the region.

After Saudi Arabia and other OPEC+ states decided that they would slow down oil production, I believe that relations between the United States and Saudi Arabia will sour and prospects of normalized relations between Saudi Arabia and Israel will remain cold.
Lowering the probability a bit because the status hasn't really changed, and there isn't a motivation for it to happen.

In considering this question, it is important to note that a full-blown military alliance is not in Saudi Arabia's interests. While Israel and the U.S. push such an alliance to counter what Israel considers to be an existential threat in Iran, Saudi Arabia would put itself in harm's way if it lined up with Israel. Saudi Arabia is closer to Iran and does not have the same defensive capabilities that Israel has. Even if the two countries shared technology as part of an alliance, Israel would not share everything because of its military edge doctrine. The United States' commitment to defend Saudi in event of a war is questionable given U.S. public opinion. That is why Saudi Arabia has been willing to talk to Iran in past months and uses less combative rhetoric than Israel.
I'm going to hold this level of probability for now, nothing has really changed in the last few days.

The decision of OPEC Plus, led by Saudi Arabia and Russia, shows that Saudi Arabia is looking to chart a course that is more independent of the United States. By cutting production and increasing oil prices, Saudi Arabia is reneging on a promise to increase production through the end of 2022, regardless of the benefits that higher prices will bring to Russia. For Saudi Arabia, stabilizing oil markets in cooperation with Russia and Iran is more important than pleasing the United States.
My initial assessment of this event occurring has not changed. A necessary but not sufficient condition for this event to occur is significant progress on the Israeli - Palestinian conflict.

SA has said explicitly it will not do this without a Palestinian two state solution. Israel has stated willingness for a 2-state solution, but there are obvious roadblocks including the fact that Israel's negotiating partner is divided and legitimacy for a solution among all the factions would be difficult (at least by March, 2023). Things seem to be trending in the right direction, but that's it for now.
I'm raising the probability a little bit, because I think there is a slight possibility they could work together (even just a little bit), in forming an alliance with other nations against Iran.
The prince wants to make a name for himself globally. A good name.
Israel's current government has declared its support for the two-state solution, but the unlikelihood of actually achieving such a solution means that the move is largely symbolic.

I keep my forecast at 20% because it seems that there may very well be world events (such as those in China, and Iran) which may lead to Saudi Arabia beginning to normalize relations with the State of Israel.

I'm keeping my prediction the same at 10% because I still think it's a possibility, but nothing has happened to indicate that Saudi Arabia would want to make any moves in this direction.

With the conflict in Azerbaijan and Armenia intensifying, Saudi Arabia and Israel will need to refocus their efforts on securing the neighboring countries in terms of security to protect against a larger conflict with massive spillover. As the war in Ukraine continues to strain supply chains in Europe for energy, Saudi Arabia will need to also focus on maintaining relations with Russia and decide if it will supply Europe with necessary energy supplies during the winter. The focus of Saudi Arabia will be less on normalizing relations with Israel and more on dancing a fine line with Russia.
I still doubt that this will happen, unless significant government changes happen in November.

I predict no, it is highly unlikely that Saudi Arabia will normalize relations with the State of Israel. It would require a major world event as well as a common enemy.

One agreement is that commercial planes will be able to fly between the two countries. think it will require a common enemy or a giant crisis that will force the two countries into normalizing relations.

There is certainly economic and political convergence taking place between the two countries, and the behind-the-scenes nature of their relationship has come to light this year. Thus, it is definitely possible SA will one day normalize relations, though I doubt before March, 2023 for the same reasons as my last forecast.

Another dimension to this question is economic. Saudi Arabia and Israel have growing business ties, but the state of official relations poses difficulties. Direct money transfers and even phone calls between the two countries aren't possible. If MBS is serious about his plans for modernizing Saudi Arabia, he would consider deeper partnership with Israel, the Middle East's "Silicon Valley." However, because of the deep opposition to Israel among the public and religious elites, he will probably aim for closer unofficial relations in the near-term.

The probability that Saudi Arabia will normalize relations with Israel by March 2023 is low. While Israel and Saudi Arabia will continue to share regional and geopolitical interests, complete normalization is unlikely to happen in such a brief time span of only 5 months

Saudi Arabia is unique among Arab countries for its occasional support of the Israeli state. However, this support does not mean relations are likely to be normalized. Saudi Arabia has many international interests in its Arab neighbors, from trade to mutual defense, and normalizing relations could harm those relations. Israel is not a major trade partner of Saudi Arabia but it is a mutual ally in opposition to Iran, who poses a security threat to both nations. This mutual threat does not constitute enough to justify normalization but it does mean that the two countries will continue to provide limited aid to one another in the future.

Despite recent negotiations being reopened between Israel and the Arab world, I believe there is a minimal chance of Saudi Arabia attempting to normalize relations with Israel in this timeframe. Israel and Morocco recently opened ties, but Morocco is known to be more hospitable than Saudi Arabia to its Jewish population, as well as seeing considerable benefits in terms of commerce from such recognition with Israel. Saudi Arabia does not need these benefits, and they would be negligible as is, not to mention Saudi Arabia's noted hostility to Israel.

I'm going to keep my prediction steady as I don't think anything can change between the two countries that quickly. The below article illustrates more of my thoughts that even if they are being politically cordial, the relationship won't change that fast or willingly.
It's simply an unrealistic timeline for Saudi Arabia to normalize its relations so quickly.

I think there is always a chance Saudi Arabia would announce this, but it is highly doubtful to me. Israel has been controversial in the Middle East for hundreds of years and I don't think that Saudi Arabia has the economic or political incentives to normalize relations yet.

This is a somewhat difficult prediction, as there is no concrete information in sources. It is seems like a "this information vs. the other information" debate. However, from what I gather, Saudi Arabia will not normalize relations with the State of Palestine until there is movement to resolve the Palestinian conflict. International negotiation is sometimes difficult--there can be no progress for weeks or all of a sudden there is a leaps-and-bounds change. Although a bit of an exaggeration If, or when, Saudi Arabia normalizes relations with the State of Israel, it will be the "deal of the century".
I think this would be too soon. The Saudis will not want to give Biden a political 'victory' as they are hoping for Trump's reelection in 2024 (assuming he may run).

I do not predict Saudi Arabia and Israel will normalize their relations before March 2023. I do not see that Israel will change their position towards Palestine relatively soon which is a major hinderance for normalized relations between the House of Saud and Israel. Even though the two countries share an commonality in their views towards Iran and Islamic opponents, I do not believe that is enough of an incentive.

I predict that Saudi Arabia will not normalize relations with Israel before 2023. There must be a resolution over the Palinistine crisis before Saudia Arabia could begin to consider normalizing relationship with Isreal. When President Biden went to meet with Saudi King Salman and Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman he brought up the possibility of normalizing relations with Israel. The Suadi government made it clear that Palestine needs to be resolved or their government will refuse to make any progress with Israel.

Saudi Arabia will normalize relations with Israel if it believes that such a policy will aid regime survival. Currently, Saudi Arabia and Israel have extensive covert contacts, so the issue is whether going public with relations will strengthen MBS's position.

Given the intractable nature of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, expectations of significant movement toward the ‘two state solution’, Israel’s security dilemma with respect to asymmetric conflict on its borders and within its territory, preconditions for discussions are premature well into the next decade (if not longer).
